observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Management require:

the Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor, to expedite the updating of the RPTAR, to facilitate the preparation of the list of taxpayers showing the names and the amounts due and collectible, which will serve as basis by the Municipal Accountant in setting up receivables from RPT and SET;

the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjustments in the books to reconcile the balances of RPT Receivables, Deferred RPT, SET Receivables and Deferred RPT with the list provided by the Municipal Treasurer to ensure reliability of the balances presented in the financial statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. Inventory Committee to complete the procedures for One-time cleansing of PPE of the Municipality in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 and submit the required report thereon;
b. Municipal Accountant to re-classify/adjust to Government Equity the semi-expendable properties still in the PPE in compliance with COA Circular No. 2022-004;
c. Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of inventory and submit the Report on the Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) to the Audit Team in compliance with Section 124, Chapter 7 of MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I; and
d. Municipal Accountant and the OIC-Municipal GSO to prepare and maintain the Property Cards for all properties of the Municipality and to disclose the total road network system of the Municipality as required in COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We reiterated our recommendations that the Municipal Mayor:
a. instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct complete physical count of the entire Municipality’s PPE and correspondingly prepare and submit to the Audit Team the required report thereon; 
b. direct the OIC-GSO to prepare and maintain the Property Cards for all properties of the Municipality and the Property Acknowledgement Receipts for issued properties; 
c. direct the Municipal Accountant and the OIC-Municipal GSO, to conduct the required reconciliation of their records with the inventory report and adjust their records, if necessary, to present the true balance of PPE accounts in the financial statements; 
d. conduct One-time Cleansing of PPE pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006 and prepare the JEVs to effect the One-Time Cleansing; and 
e. henceforth, strictly comply with Section 6.3 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended that:
a. Management require the members of the Inventory Committee, in coordination with the personnel concerned, to prioritize the conduct of complete inventory-taking activities, reconciliation with pertinent records, and preparation and submission of reports, for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts pursuant to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006;
b. Municipal Accountant prepare the journal entries necessary to derecognize the items below the ₱50.000.00 capitalization threshold and still on process;
c. the General Services Officer (GSO) carry out control procedures for the maintenance of semi-expendable property records, pursuant to COA Circular Nos. 2022-004 and 2024-006; and
d. Municipal Accountant and the GSO ensure that proper accounting and reporting procedures for all acquisition/receipt/issue/transfer/disposal of PPE pursuant to the relevant laws, rules and regulations on property and supply management are strictly followed. The Municipal Mayor should likewise ensure that physical inventory is undertaken annually and reports thereon are submitted accordingly.

We recommended that the:
a. Municipal Accountant and the GSO maintain complete and updated LRNLCs and LRNPCs, respectively, to cause the proper reconciliation with the RPCLRN, in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2015-008;
b. Municipal Mayor ensure the reconciliation of the Local Road Inventory with the records maintained by the Municipal Accountant and the GSO.

We recommended, and Management agreed to direct the:

a. Inventory Committee to – 

1. Prepare the PIP, and submit the same to the Municipal Mayor for approval to ensure that the conduct of inventory-taking is properly and adequately planned pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006;

2. Submit a copy of the approved PIP to COA at least 10 calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities;

3. Prepare a detailed and properly-filled consolidated RPCPPE and submit to the MGSO and Municipal Accountant for reconciliation of PPE items with their corresponding records and investigate discrepancies thereof; and

4. Strictly conduct the inventory taking in accordance with the procedures prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006.

b. Municipal Treasurer as the Designated MGSO to – 

5. Request the disposal of unserviceable properties by filling-up of the IIRUP and proceed with disposal procedures either thru sale, donation, or destruction following Section 379 of RA No. 7160 and the Manual on the Disposal of Government Property per COA DBM Joint Circular 2024-01;

6. Submit to the Municipal Accountant the duly approved IIRUP and disposal documents for recording in the books of accounts, after the completion of the disposal process; and

7. Municipal Accountant to record adjustments after completion of proper reconciliation to establish the correct balances of PPE and other affected accounts, supported with appropriate documents.

We recommended, and Management agreed to direct the:

36. Municipal Engineer to immediately conduct regular review and evaluation of unimplemented projects and expedite the preparation of necessary documents to facilitate the request for procurement and implementation of these projects;

37. Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator to re-assess the projects funded under the 20 per cent current appropriations as to viability, feasibility, and relevance, and endorse the results thereof to the Municipal Development Council for appropriate action;

38. Municipal Agriculturist to ensure that for programs and projects that fall under the agricultural development has to be implementable ready in order to optimize the benefits that can be obtained therefrom; and 

39. Ensure that identification of projects to be funded out of the 20 per cent DF are well planned, and procurement-and-implementation ready to avoid implementation issues such as lot/area for implementation.

45. Send demand letters to concerned accountable officers and employees with unsettled accounts for its immediate settlement. In case of non-settlement of employees who are still connected with the LGU, cause the withholding of salaries or any money claims due them;

46. Take appropriate actions on the unsettled accounts of accountable officers who are no longer connected or not in active service with the LGU; and

47. Request for write-off of dormant accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016, if warranted.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
(i) exhaust all possible means to recover the amount equivalent to undeposited collections and the unpresented AFs from the concerned AO, otherwise, initiate filing of appropriate charges to the Office of the Ombudsman and/or claims against the Fidelity Fund;
(ii) instruct the Municipal Treasurer to (a) closely monitor and supervise all concerned AOs and ensure that all collections are remitted and deposited intact daily and/or the next banking day, to prevent the risks of theft, loss and/or misapplication; and (b) see to it that all the necessary details and required information are duly indicated in the ORs and RCDs;
(iii) instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the undeposited collections to its proper accounts and submit to the Audit Team the accountable forms not presented for audit, to facilitate verification thereof; and
(iv) install, implement and monitor a sound internal control system that would facilitate proper check and balance between the Accounting and MTO so as to immediately detect possible fraudulent/erroneous activities to minimize, if not avoid the possible risks of loss of public funds.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that the Municipal Mayor to require the Municipal Accountant to:
• Ensure that receivables for RPT and SET be recognized at the beginning of the year in accordance with Section 20 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
• In coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, analyze and reconcile the discrepancy in the recorded balances of RPT and SET Receivables as against the total amount of tax delinquencies indicated in the Real Property Tax Owners Delinquency Listing and prepare the necessary adjusting entry to present the correct and reliable balances of RPT and SET Receivable accounts in the financial statements as at year-end;
• Ensure that advance payments received are deducted from the related RPT and SET Receivables and their deferred accounts in the year they are earned; and
• Analyze the net effect of the foregoing observations in the financial statements and draw the necessary adjusting entries in the General and Special Education Fund books to reflect the correct balance of the affected accounts.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Treasurer to:
• exert more effort and undertake effective, efficient and aggressive tax collection strategies to improve collection by conducting massive tax campaigns and consistent preparation and issuance of Notices of Delinquency for all delinquent Real Property Units;
• monitor the payment of real property taxes due for the current year and impose the available remedies and procedures as authorized under the Local Government Code;
• for the delinquent real property taxes with NDs already served, recommend to the Provincial Treasurer the imposition of the legal remedies either by administrative auction thru levy on real property or judicial action, following the procedures authorized in the LGC, to enforce collection and to undertake the same expeditiously on a yearly basis to reduce amounts accumulated as receivables for delinquent taxes; and
• conduct dialogue with owners different from the records on file to address concerns on the collection of taxes. If warranted, request the presence of the Provincial Treasurer and Provincial Legal Officer to assist in such undertaking.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
a. BAC and its TWG to: (i) revisit the updated guidelines and provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and GPPB Resolutions to ensure that all procurement activities undertaken by the Municipality are strictly in accordance with the provisions of the updated 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; (ii) be cautious and exercise prudence in the examination of eligibility and technical documents submitted by the prospective bidders in faithful adherence to relevant provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 to prevent the award of contract to ineligible contractors/suppliers; (iii) immediately submit the lacking bidding documents to the Audit Team to arrive at a decision in audit; (iv) ensure strict compliance with the provisions set forth in Rule No. 36 of the IRR of Republic Act No. 9502 and EO No. 49 regarding the procurement of drugs and medicines; and (v) strictly comply with the prescribed period of furnishing the COA Auditor copies of contracts including the documentary requirements to facilitate timely review and evaluation as prescribed by COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009 and COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 as amended;
b. Municipal Engineer to ensure that the amounts of components indicated in the DUPA or Detailed Estimates tally/match with the amounts of components in the ABC and POW;
c. Municipal Accountant to: (i) immediately submit the noted lacking supporting documents and ensure that all claims are duly supported with proper and complete supporting documents, as required under COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012, with amendments on Item 9.1.3.1 under COA Circular No. 2024-010 dated July 31, 2024, before processing claims for payment; and (ii) impose and issue order of payment for liquidated damages for the delays incurred by the consultant;
d. MDRRM Officer to submit a justification on the use of service vehicle by the same driver at nearly the same time across different destinations; and
e. Municipal Treasurer to secure the official receipts of payments upon issuance of checks to the winning bidders.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Prepare the Subsidiary Ledgers maintained for Accounts Payable to show the details of the transactions;
b. Submit to the Audit Team the accurate/reliable Aging of Accounts Payable;
c. Prepare Journal Entry Vouchers to adjust errors in recording transactions totaling P54,682.99 by debiting Accounts Payable and crediting appropriate liability accounts; and
d. Strictly adhere on the provision of Section 111 of PD No. 1445 on keeping the accounts of the Municipality.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (LDRRMO) to:
a. Explain the non-implementation of 15 identified LDRRMF Programs and the excess disbursement on the four completed projects;
b. Carefully plan the programs funded under the LDRRMF to be conducted for the year and fast-track its implementation to ensure that the constituents enjoy the benefits that they could derived from these projects;
c. Analyze the feasibility of implementing the CO projects under the Continuing Appropriation of LDRRMF, and recommend on the projects to be funded for available LDRRMF; and
d. Strictly comply with the guidelines set out in COA Circular No. 2012-002 on the proper accounting and reporting, and the utilization of the LDRRMF.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Review and analyze all payables that remained outstanding at year-end, including the beginning balance totaling P30,672,737.13 by gathering the necessary documents to substantiate the existence of valid claims, in compliance with Section 46 of PD No. 1177;
b. If warranted, seek authority, from the Sangguniang Bayan (SB), to revert to the unappropriated surplus the payable accounts having no valid claims which were outstanding for more than two years and hereinafter, observe the prescribed period for the retention of Accounts Payable in the Books of accounts in accordance with Section 98 of PD No. 1445;
c. Make necessary adjusting journal entry reversing liabilities which are not legitimate obligations of the Municipality; and
d. Exert due care in the recording of transactions with complete documentation and establish the accurate amount of the Accounts Payable to achieve fair presentation of that account in the financial statements.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor:
a. Direct the concerned Offices to send representative to public procurement training program for capacity building on the preparation of PPMPs;
b. Instruct all implementing units to prepare and submit, on a timely manner, their respective PPMPs prior to the preparation of the consolidated APP in the prescribed format of the GPPB, which include, but not limited to, supplies, materials, equipment and infrastructure projects to be implemented during the current year/succeeding years, and submit to the Municipal Budget Office for evaluation; 
c. Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to furnish a copy of the procuring entity's budget proposal, as well as the corresponding PPMPs of all implementing units or end-user Offices, to the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) Secretariat for its review and consolidation into the proposed APP, consistent with the procuring entity's budget proposal, pursuant to Section 7.3.4 of the same IRR; and
d. Direct the BAC, thru its BAC Secretariat, to finalize the modes of procurement under the proposed APP, in accordance with Section 7 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184.

We recommended that Management:
a. review the Municipality's organizational structure and staffing pattern to ensure alignment with service requirements and financial capabilities, while complying with CSC guidelines;
b. develop and implement a strategic human resources plan focused on recruiting and retaining personnel to fill vacant plantilla positions, while deploying COS personnel strategically to support critical service areas; 
c. conduct regular assessments of staffing needs and establish mechanisms to address gaps and optimize human resources utilization; and
d. create avenues for COS personnel to obtain the required eligibility qualifications and improve their pertinent skills, ensuring fair treatment and equal access to career advancement opportunities for all.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:

The Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor, to prepare and furnish the Municipal Accountant a duly certified list of taxpayers showing the names and the amounts due and collectible based on updated Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayer’s Index Card to ensure an accurate and reliable basis in setting up the Receivables from RPT and SET;

The Municipal Accountant to draw a Journal Entry Voucher to record the RPT/SET Receivables established at the beginning of the year based on the submitted duly certified list of taxpayers by the Municipal Treasurer with the amount due and collectible for the year and maintain the corresponding subsidiary ledgers for proper accounting and monitoring of tax collections and delinquencies.

We recommended that the Management, thru the Local Chief Executive, undertake the following courses of action:

Require the Municipal Development Council to specify the details of the identified priority projects to be charged under the 20% Development Fund in the total amount of P24,189,780.08, including project location, specific implementation schedule, and physical target pursuant to Article 454(d) of the Implementing Rules and Regulations of Local Government Code of 1991 (RA 7160);

Stop the practice of implementing generic or lumpsum projects without further authority from the Sanggunian to avoid suspension/disallowance in audit.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. OIC-Municipal Accountant to effect the immediate adjustment of valid reconciling items in the books of accounts to ensure the correctness of the account balances appearing in the Municipality’s financial statements at any given time;
b. OIC-Municipal Accountant to investigate the previous years’ transactions in the Trust Fund account booked as deposits with a total amount of P95,300.00 but still not reflected in the Municipality’s bank account. In the event that the underlying cause of discrepancy cannot be identified, a Notice of Charge shall be issued for the amount of P95,300.00 to the Municipal Official/employee who have been determined to be liable for the transaction;
c. OIC-Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to closely coordinate with each other to promptly resolve any unrecorded deposits, collections and disbursements appearing in the reconciliation and ensure these were recorded accordingly; and henceforth,
d. strictly adhere to the provision of COA Circular No. 96-011 dated October 2, 1996.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor file the request for authority to write-off duly supported with complete relevant documents to the Commission on Audit through the Audit Team Leader (ATL) and/or Supervising Auditor (SA). The request shall be supported by the following documents:
a. schedule of dormant accounts by accountable officer/debtor/government entity and by account, certified by the Accountant and approved by the Head of the government entity;
b. certification by the responsible officials of the entity to the effect that there are no records/documents available to validate claim;
c. proof of exhaustion of all remedies to collect the receivables; and
d. other justifications, like in the case of request for write-off due to loss of documents, the circumstances of the loss should be stated in the letter-request.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant and OIC-Municipal General Services Officer (MGSO) to:
a. reconcile the net variance of P19,205,065.70 between the Detailed Statement of Financial Position and RPCPPE;
b. conduct One-Time Cleansing of PPE account pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006;
c. prepare JEVs to effect the One-Time Cleansing of PPE account; and
d. henceforth, strictly comply with Section 6.3 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

Send demand letters to concerned accountable officers and employees with unsettled accounts for its immediate settlement. In case of non-settlement of employees who are still connected with the LGU, cause the withholding of salaries or any money claims due them;

Take appropriate actions on the unsettled accounts of accountable officers who are no longer connected or not in active service with the LGU; and

Request for write-off of dormant accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016, if warranted.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Require the accounting office to make the necessary adjustment in the books of the LGU for the 20% to be held in trust for the OBO operation and DPWH shares;
Account separately the 15% share of building permit fees and other charges, and maintain a separate Trust Fund or Trust Liability account and thereafter, the Building Official shall prepare a Program of Work detailing the manner of utilization of the 15% share to be held under trust, to be approved by the Local Chief Executive, and to be submitted to the DPWH Secretary thru the NCBDO;
Direct the Accounting Office to record 80% of the collection as income under the General Fund, the 15% as Trust Liability under the Trust Fund books and the 5% as Due to National Government Agencies; and
Direct the Treasury Office to make full remittance of the 5% DPWH Share within the prescribed period.

We recommended that the Management require:
the Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor, to expedite the updating of the RPTAR, to facilitate the preparation of the list of taxpayers showing the names and the amounts due and collectible, which will serve as basis by the Municipal Accountant in setting up receivables from RPT and SET;
the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjustments in the books to reconcile the balances of RPT Receivables, Deferred RPT, SET Receivables and Deferred RPT with the list provided by the Municipal Treasurer to ensure reliability of the balances presented in the financial statements.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Mayor:
a. instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct complete physical count of the entire Municipality’s PPE and correspondingly prepare and submit to the Audit Team the required Detailed Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);
b. direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant and the OIC-Municipal General Services Office to conduct the required reconciliation of their records with the inventory report and adjust their records, if necessary, to present the true balance of PPE accounts in the financial statements;
c. conduct One-time Cleansing of PPE account pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-06;
d. instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) to effect the One-Time Cleansing; and henceforth,
e. strictly comply with the Section 6.3 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the HRMO to:
a. establish and develop written policy guidelines for the hiring of JO/CoS personnel that clearly define the conditions for availing of JO/CoS personnel and specify criteria for determining a daily wage rate that is fair and consistent across the Municipality;
b. assess the existing organizational structure and staffing pattern of the Municipality to determine the ideal number of plantilla items/positions needed to carry out the Municipality’s operations efficiently and effectively;
c. consider those qualified JO/CoS personnel for appointment to vacant regular plantilla positions in the Municipality; and henceforth,
d. strictly comply with Sections 76 and 77 of RA No. 7160.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Mayor:
a. instruct the LDRRMO to strictly follow the guidelines in the preparation of LDRRMFIP and submit to the OCD and DILG-MLGOO and to the COA a copy of fully compliant LDRRMFIP;
b. require the LDRRMO and OIC-Municipal Accountant to submit the monthly Report on the Sources and Utilization of DRRMF within the prescribed period.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:
a. coordinate with the Municipal Legal Officer, to exhaust all possible means to collect the dormant accounts;
b. prepare all the necessary supporting documents to substantiate the Municipality’s request for write-off in accordance with COA Circular No. 2016-05.

observations.managementAction:
In a letter dated April 29, 2024, the General Services Officer commented the following:
• Drafting of PIP in a timely manner and forwarding the same to the Municipal Mayor for review and approval pursuant to COA Circular;
• The IC will ensure all details and data are finalized and documented after review and approval of the PIP. Subsequent submission of the same to the Audit Team within the specified period;
• Once finalization of the details needed in the sticker to be printed, their Office will start to implement by affixing temporary control stickers to the inventoried PPE;
• Prompt compilation of the list to ensure compliance with the procedure of proper accountability for the missing items;
• Instructions was given already to Property Inventory Section (PIS) to promptly implement the use of pre-numbered property tags and to ensure the same contain the required information;
• Ensure strict compliance with the requirement by issuance of PARs to all issued PPE items and instructions was given to PIS to ensure that PARs are renewed or updated every three years; and
• The GSO will actively coordinate with the OMA and IC to conduct the required procedures in accordance with the pertinent provisions of the Circular.

observations.recommendation:
