a. assess the existing organization structure and staffing pattern of the Municipality so that the ideal number of plantilla items/positions could be established and develop a written policy guideline on the hiring of individuals under JO, clearly defining the conditions whereby employment of such JO personnel may be availed of;
b. consider those qualified JO personnel for appointment to casual or vacant regular plantilla positions in the agency.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:
The Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Assessor, to prepare and furnish the Municipal Accountant a duly certified list of taxpayers showing the names and the amounts due and collectible based on updated Real Property Tax Account Register/Taxpayer’s Index Card to ensure an accurate and reliable basis in setting up the Receivables from RPT and SET;
The Municipal Accountant to draw a Journal Entry Voucher to record the RPT/SET Receivables established at the beginning of the year based on the submitted duly certified list of taxpayers by the Municipal Treasurer with the amount due and collectible for the year and maintain the corresponding subsidiary ledgers for proper accounting and monitoring of tax collections and delinquencies.

We recommended that the Management, thru the Local Chief Executive, undertake the following courses of action:
Require the Municipal Development Council to specify the details of the identified priority projects to be charged under the 20% Development Fund in the total amount of P24,189,780.08, including project location, specific implementation schedule, and physical target pursuant to Article 454(d) of the Implementing Rules and Regulations of Local Government Code of 1991 (RA 7160);
Stop the practice of implementing generic or lumpsum projects without further authority from the Sanggunian to avoid suspension/disallowance in audit.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor to:
a) require an annual physical inventory of all the supplies and materials of the Municipality to be conducted by a committee consisting of representative from the Office of the Municipal Mayor, Municipal General Services Officer and Supply Accountable Officer of the department or office concerned;
b) designate an additional staff in the Accounting Office to undertake the preparation and maintenance of Supplies Ledger Card (SLC) needed to track the receipts and issuance of supplies and materials;
c) require the GSO to maintain Stock Cards (SCs) for the recording of receipts and issuances of supplies and materials and submit to the Municipal Accountant the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and distribution report within five days after the end of each month; and
d) require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that SSMI, distribution reports and other pertinent documents were attached to the Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) in recording issuances of supplies and materials and regularly conduct reconciliation of inventory records with GSO.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the responsible officials to:
a. utilize the funds for the intended purpose;
b. submit the liquidation reports of fund transfers from the National Government Agencies in compliance with COA Circular No. 94-013;
c. immediately return to the Source Agency the unutilized funds; and
d. provide copies of MOAs and other pertinent documents to the Office of the Auditor to facilitate the evaluation of the PPAs.

We also recommended the Municipal Accountant to exert extra effort to look for the documents supporting the non-moving and ascertain why the same remained in the books.

